        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Ops Role in LLMOps"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Ops role in an LLMOps team is the operational nervous system: it owns the on-call rotation, triages production incidents, maintains the guardrail and evaluation pipeline health, manages provider relationships, and ensures that every incident produces a feedback signal that improves the system. Where Infra builds and maintains the platform, Ops runs it day-to-day. The distinction matters most under pressure: when a quality regression appears at 2 AM, Ops is the function that detects it, mitigates it, and begins the feedback loop that prevents recurrence."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Incident Response Lifecycle"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Ops incident-to-iteration flow: Detect \u2192 Triage \u2192 Mitigate \u2192 Diagnose \u2192 Fix Signal \u2192 Iterate \u2192 Verify \u2192 Close, with on-call responsibilities shown below."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The eight-step loop above is the Ops role's core operational pattern. Steps 1\u20134 (detect to diagnose) are time-critical and typically completed within an SLA (e.g. P1 within 30 minutes). Steps 5\u20138 (fix signal to close) close the feedback loop and can take hours to days depending on complexity."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "1. Alert Triage and Severity Classification"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Ops role is the first responder when a monitoring alert fires. The first decision is severity classification: what is broken, how many users are affected, and how fast is it getting worse? An incorrect severity classification wastes escalation time or under-responds to a genuine incident."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import List, Optional\nfrom enum import Enum\n\nclass Severity(str, Enum):\n    P1 = \"P1\"   # production broken for all users; respond in < 15 min\n    P2 = \"P2\"   # quality degraded for > 10 % of users; respond in < 1 h\n    P3 = \"P3\"   # quality degraded for < 10 % of users; respond in < 4 h\n    P4 = \"P4\"   # minor issue; address in next sprint\n\n@dataclass\nclass IncidentSignal:\n    alert_name: str\n    model: str\n    stage: str              # production | canary | shadow\n    metric_value: float\n    threshold: float\n    affected_user_pct: float    # estimated from trace sampling\n    duration_minutes: float\n\n    def classify_severity(self) -> Severity:\n        if self.affected_user_pct > 50 or self.alert_name in (\"guardrail_surge\", \"total_outage\"):\n            return Severity.P1\n        if self.affected_user_pct > 10 or self.duration_minutes > 30:\n            return Severity.P2\n        if self.affected_user_pct > 2:\n            return Severity.P3\n        return Severity.P4\n\n@dataclass\nclass Incident:\n    incident_id: str\n    signal: IncidentSignal\n    severity: Severity\n    commander: str          # ops engineer on-call\n    opened_at: float\n    resolved_at: Optional[float] = None\n    root_cause: Optional[str] = None\n    mitigation: Optional[str] = None\n\n    @property\n    def ttm_minutes(self) -> Optional[float]:\n        \"\"\"Time-to-mitigate in minutes.\"\"\\\"\n        if self.resolved_at is None:\n            return None\n        return (self.resolved_at - self.opened_at) / 60\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
