      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import time\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom typing import Optional\n\n@dataclass\nclass Runbook:\n    incident_class: str\n    steps: list[str]\n    rollback_command: Optional[str] = None\n    escalation_contact: str = \"infra-oncall\"\n\n    def execute_step(self, step_index: int) -> str:\n        if step_index >= len(self.steps):\n            return \"runbook_complete\"\n        return self.steps[step_index]\n\nROLLBACK_RUNBOOK = Runbook(\n    incident_class=\"quality_regression_after_deploy\",\n    steps=[\n        \"1. Confirm quality drop in Grafana judge-score panel (> 5 min sustained)\",\n        \"2. Identify the deployment that preceded the drop (check deployment log)\",\n        \"3. Set feature flag 'new_prompt_v{N}' rollout_pct = 0 via config API\",\n        \"4. Verify judge score recovers within 10 minutes on the dashboard\",\n        \"5. Sample 10 failing traces and attach to incident ticket\",\n        \"6. Hand off to Data role for root cause analysis\",\n    ],\n    rollback_command=\"python scripts/set_flag.py --flag new_prompt_v{N} --pct 0\",\n    escalation_contact=\"data-oncall\",\n)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "3. Guardrail Operations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Guardrails are not set-and-forget: they need active tuning to stay calibrated as the user population and query distribution evolve. The Ops role owns guardrail health monitoring and tuning."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "False Positive Rate Management"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A guardrail that triggers too often blocks legitimate queries and degrades user experience. The Ops role tracks the false positive rate (FPR) weekly and adjusts sensitivity thresholds when FPR exceeds the product's tolerance."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import List\n\n@dataclass\nclass GuardrailMetrics:\n    window_days: int\n    total_requests: int\n    triggered_count: int\n    human_reviewed_count: int\n    true_positive_count: int    # genuine harmful content correctly blocked\n    false_positive_count: int   # legitimate content incorrectly blocked\n\n    @property\n    def trigger_rate(self) -> float:\n        return self.triggered_count / max(self.total_requests, 1)\n\n    @property\n    def precision(self) -> float:\n        \"\"\"Of blocked requests, what fraction were genuinely harmful?\"\"\\\"\n        return self.true_positive_count / max(self.triggered_count, 1)\n\n    @property\n    def false_positive_rate(self) -> float:\n        return self.false_positive_count / max(self.total_requests, 1)\n\n    def health_status(self, max_fpr: float = 0.005) -> str:\n        \"\"\"FPR > 0.5 % (5 in 1000 legitimate queries) is action-required.\"\"\\\"\n        if self.false_positive_rate > max_fpr:\n            return \"action_required: FPR too high, loosen guardrail sensitivity\"\n        if self.trigger_rate > 0.05:\n            return \"investigate: trigger rate > 5 %, possible adversarial campaign\"\n        return \"healthy\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Adversarial Corpus Expansion"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every confirmed guardrail bypass (a harmful query that was not caught) should be added to the adversarial test corpus. The Ops role coordinates this with the Data role: Ops identifies the bypass in production traces; Data labels it, adds it to the corpus, and re-runs the guardrail eval."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "4. Evaluation Pipeline Health"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The online evaluation pipeline \u2014 the judge that scores production traces asynchronously \u2014 is itself a system that can fail. If the judge model is down, rate-limited, or producing unreliable scores, the Ops role's quality dashboard goes dark. The Ops role monitors the eval pipeline and alerts on stale judge scores."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import time\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass\nfrom typing import Optional\n\n@dataclass\nclass EvalPipelineHealth:\n    last_judge_score_ts: float        # Unix timestamp of the most recent score\n    scores_per_hour_7d_avg: float     # baseline throughput\n    scores_per_hour_1h: float         # current throughput\n    judge_model: str\n    judge_error_rate_1h: float        # fraction of judge calls that failed\n\n    def is_stale(self, max_gap_minutes: float = 30.0) -> bool:\n        age_minutes = (time.time() - self.last_judge_score_ts) / 60\n        return age_minutes > max_gap_minutes\n\n    def throughput_drop(self) -> float:\n        \"\"\"Ratio of current vs baseline; < 0.5 means significant degradation.\"\"\\\"\n        return self.scores_per_hour_1h / max(self.scores_per_hour_7d_avg, 1)\n\n    def health_status(self) -> str:\n        if self.is_stale():\n            return \"critical: no judge scores in > 30 min \u2014 check judge model API\"\n        if self.judge_error_rate_1h > 0.10:\n            return \"warning: judge error rate > 10 % \u2014 check rate limits\"\n        if self.throughput_drop() < 0.5:\n            return \"warning: eval throughput dropped 50 % \u2014 check backlog\"\n        return \"healthy\"\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "5. Provider Relationship Management"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When the serving infrastructure routes to a managed LLM API (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google, etc.), the Ops role is responsible for managing that relationship operationally:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Quota management",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": track rate-limit headroom per API key and per model tier. Request quota increases proactively (typically 2\u20134 weeks lead time) before anticipated traffic spikes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Incident communication",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": subscribe to provider status pages and map provider incidents to internal severity. A provider degradation affecting response times is an Ops incident even though the root cause is external."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Version deprecation tracking",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": provider models are deprecated on announced timelines. The Ops role tracks deprecation dates, coordinates model migration with Data and Product, and ensures that migration is completed before the deprecation date."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Cost reporting",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": generate weekly cost-per-model-per-feature reports and share them with Product. Token cost surprises at the end of a billing cycle are an Ops failure."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "6. On-Call Rotation Design"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Ops role defines and maintains the on-call rotation. Effective LLMOps on-call has three properties that differ from traditional software on-call."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Judge literacy",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": on-call engineers must be able to read judge score trends and interpret whether a drop reflects a real quality issue or a judge model anomaly. This requires product knowledge, not just infrastructure knowledge."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Prompt context",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": on-call engineers need read access to the current production prompt and the prompt change log. A quality drop is undiagnosable without knowing what changed in the prompt in the preceding 48 hours."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Bounded blast radius",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": every alert should have a pre-approved mitigation that does not require waking up additional people for approval. If rolling back a prompt requires a VP approval at 3 AM, the on-call rotation is not operationally mature."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Write runbooks in plain language. An on-call engineer at 3 AM should be able to execute the mitigation steps without understanding the underlying system deeply. The runbook is the Ops role's primary artefact \u2014 it encodes operational knowledge in a form that survives team turnover."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "7. Postmortem Culture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every P1 and P2 incident should produce a written postmortem within 48 hours of resolution. The postmortem is not a blame assignment \u2014 it is a systems analysis that produces actionable improvements."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass, field\nfrom typing import List\n\n@dataclass\nclass ActionItem:\n    description: str\n    owner: str               # \"data\" | \"infra\" | \"product\" | \"ops\"\n    due_date: str            # ISO date string\n    status: str = \"open\"     # \"open\" | \"in_progress\" | \"done\"\n\n@dataclass\nclass Postmortem:\n    incident_id: str\n    severity: str\n    summary: str                     # one-paragraph plain-language summary\n    timeline: List[str]              # ordered list of events with timestamps\n    root_cause: str                  # the single most important cause\n    contributing_factors: List[str]  # secondary causes\n    what_went_well: List[str]\n    what_went_badly: List[str]\n    action_items: List[ActionItem]\n    authored_by: str\n    reviewed_by: List[str]\n\n    def open_actions(self) -> List[ActionItem]:\n        return [a for a in self.action_items if a.status == \"open\"]\n\n    def to_markdown(self) -> str:\n        lines = [\n            f\"# Postmortem: {self.incident_id} ({self.severity})\",\n            f\"\\n## Summary\\n{self.summary}\",\n            \"\\n## Timeline\",\n        ]\n        lines += [f\"- {e}\" for e in self.timeline]\n        lines += [f\"\\n## Root Cause\\n{self.root_cause}\"]\n        lines += [\"\\n## Action Items\"]\n        lines += [f\"- [ ] {a.description} ({a.owner}, due {a.due_date})\"\n                  for a in self.action_items]\n        return \"\\n\".join(lines)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
